description.narrative:
The Integrated Community Development Project (ICDP) supports 87 target Lahu communities in the 5 northern provinces of Chiang Rai, Chaing Mai, Mae Hong Son, Lampang and Tak with about 15,070 people. The communities have been encountering with personal legal status, natural resource management, rights abuse problems. Without legal status, their rights are limited to government services such as occupation, free travel, education, health care or even rights to vote or to involve in the politics. Without rights to manage the natural resources, they tend to get exploited, arrested and have difficult livelihoods.&nbsp;
The project aims that communities are able to access to government&rsquo;s legal rights services including other basic human rights issues.&nbsp;
The objectives of the project are the target communities including networks and women groups are empowered and have their capacities strengthened in approaching their basic human rights and free from exploitations.
The project expects that the target community network is strengthened to claim their basic human rights, the child and women groups access to their basic rights and free from exploitations, increased women&rsquo;s participation in decision-making in development planning, administration and governance, and collective participation of community members to advocate for just and sustainable natural resource management.
Major activities are capacity building and awareness raising, network empowerment, women and youth empowerment.
The focused thematic issues are basic human rights, gender roles, personal legal status and natural resource management.
Other stakeholders include local authorities, legal status network and environmental networks.&nbsp;
